{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"ba6a8e51-a2cd-45d5-a133-0d0468021ebb","content":"With MSTest 3.8.2, you can use **constructor injection** for `TestContext` and implement `IAsyncInitialization` for async setup:\n\n```csharp\n[TestClass]\npublic class MyTests : IAsyncInitialization\n{\n    public TestContext TestContext { get; }\n\n    // Synchronous initialization via constructor\n    public MyTests(TestContext testContext)\n    {\n        TestContext = testContext;\n        // sync setup here (e.g., create objects, set fields)\n    }\n\n    // Asynchronous initialization\n    public Task InitializeAsync()\n    {\n        // async setup here (e.g., open connections, seed data)\n        return Task.CompletedTask;\n    }\n\n    [TestMethod]\n    public void SyncTest()\n    {\n        Assert.IsNotNull(TestContext);\n    }\n\n    [TestMethod]\n    public async Task AsyncTest()\n    {\n        await Task.Delay(1);\n        Assert.IsNotNull(TestContext.TestName);\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- **Constructor injection** — MSTest 3.x injects `TestContext` automatically via the constructor parameter. No need for the old `[TestInitialize]` property setter pattern.\n- **`IAsyncInitialization`** — implement this interface when you need `await`-able setup. It runs after the constructor, before each test.\n- The classic `[TestInitialize]` / `[ClassInitialize]` attributes still work alongside this if needed.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"3fada901-d9ba-45fc-933c-893d7eee5ea0","outputTokens":362,"requestId":"5809:3CBAC0:165D41C:17D44EB:6A0338AB"},"id":"be66200f-dd28-447d-aff9-9e2ff993e593","timestamp":"2026-05-12T14:27:01.609Z","parentId":"e3e5e0de-2b9e-4691-8d3d-f6fda33823f5"}
